# Chapter 8 — Indian tabla

The tabla is a pair of drums — the smaller *dayan* on the right, the larger *bayan* on the left. Together they carry the rhythmic architecture of Hindustani classical music.

The tabla teaches your hands two different jobs at the same time. The right hand has the tuned head; the left hand has the bass and the pitch-bend. Neither hand does what the other does. That's part of what gives tabla its shape.

## The two drums

```scheme
(define (make-tabla-drum name role) (list 'drum name 'role role))

(define dayan (make-tabla-drum 'dayan 'tuned-melody))
(define bayan (make-tabla-drum 'bayan 'bass-and-bend))

(display dayan) (newline)
(display bayan) (newline)
```

Output:

```
(drum dayan role tuned-melody)
(drum bayan role bass-and-bend)
```

## The bols

Every tabla stroke has a name — a *bol*. They double as spoken words during teaching.

```scheme
(define (bol name hand stroke)
  (list 'bol name 'hand hand 'stroke stroke))

(define bols
  (list
    (bol 'na  'right 'ring-finger-edge)
    (bol 'tin 'right 'index-tap-center)
    (bol 'ta  'right 'flat-finger-edge)
    (bol 'ge  'left  'palm-heel-with-bend)
    (bol 'ka  'left  'closed-slap)))

(for-each (lambda (b) (display b) (newline)) bols)
```

Output:

```
(bol na hand right stroke ring-finger-edge)
(bol tin hand right stroke index-tap-center)
(bol ta hand right stroke flat-finger-edge)
(bol ge hand left stroke palm-heel-with-bend)
(bol ka hand left stroke closed-slap)
```

## A composed phrase — dhin dhin dha

Bols combine into phrases that describe a rhythm exactly.

```scheme
(define (compose-phrase bols) (list 'phrase bols))

(define teentaal-first-half
  (compose-phrase '(dha dhin dhin dha
                    dha dhin dhin dha)))

(display teentaal-first-half) (newline)
```

Output:

```
(phrase (dha dhin dhin dha dha dhin dhin dha))
```

The bol sequence is the composition. It's speakable, teachable, memorable.

## The talas — cyclical patterns

A *tala* is a cyclic pattern of beats.

```scheme
(define (make-tala name beats emphasis)
  (list 'tala name 'beats beats 'emphasis emphasis))

(define teentaal (make-tala 'teentaal 16 '(1 5 9 13)))
(define ektaal   (make-tala 'ektaal   12 '(1 3 5 7 9 11)))
(define jhaptaal (make-tala 'jhaptaal 10 '(1 3 6 8)))

(display teentaal) (newline)
(display ektaal) (newline)
(display jhaptaal) (newline)
```

Output:

```
(tala teentaal beats 16 emphasis (1 5 9 13))
(tala ektaal beats 12 emphasis (1 3 5 7 9 11))
(tala jhaptaal beats 10 emphasis (1 3 6 8))
```

Three talas, three cycle lengths, three emphasis patterns. Each has its own feel.

## The bend

The bayan bass has a signature pitch-bend from wrist pressure.

```scheme
(define (bayan-bend start-pitch pressure)
  (list 'bend
        'from start-pitch
        'to (list start-pitch '+ pressure)))

(display (bayan-bend 'low 'medium-wrist-press)) (newline)
```

Output:

```
(bend from low to (low + medium-wrist-press))
```

## Two-drum interplay

```scheme
(define (interplay dayan-bol bayan-bol)
  (list 'interplay 'right dayan-bol 'left bayan-bol))

(display (interplay 'na 'ge)) (newline)
(display (interplay 'tin 'ka)) (newline)
```

Output:

```
(interplay right na left ge)
(interplay right tin left ka)
```

Two drums, one gesture. That's tabla.

## What you know now

- Tabla = dayan (right, tuned) + bayan (left, bass with bend).
- Bols name every stroke and double as spoken rhythm.
- Talas are cyclic patterns of beats with emphasis positions.
- The two hands do different jobs at the same time.

## Try before you turn the page

```scheme
(display '(phrase (dha ge na dha tin ge na))) (newline)
```

If you can name the two drums and their roles, you're ready for the strings ensemble.

